  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Mark 1:29-34",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Mark 1:29-34",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They entered into the house of Simon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, of Peter. See the notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 8:14-17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And all the city was gathered together at the door ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Namely, of the house in which Jesus was; some coming as humble petitioners for themselves or their friends, others as spectators of the surprising miracles which he wrought, and some probably to hear and be instructed by his discourses. O what a fair prospect was here! Who could then have imagined that all these blossoms would die away without fruit? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he healed many ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Luke says, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 4:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He laid his hands on every one of them and healed them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The sight of so many of the humankind in distress, moved him; and he took pity on them, and cured them all. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he suffered not the devils to speak, because they knew him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Luke, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "knew that he was the Christ ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, according to the hypothesis of those who consider the Scriptural demoniacs as being only diseased persons, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he suffered not the diseases to speak, because they knew him! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The fact seems to have been this, the demons, in addressing Jesus, honoured him with the title of the Messiah. This, his enemies said, they never would have done, had he not been in compact with them. Therefore, our Lord would not have their testimony, because it was a real and intended defamation of him; and because he foresaw that it would be made a bad use of by men of evil minds.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:29-39 Wherever Christ comes, he comes to do good. He cures, that we may minister to him, and to others who are his, and for his sake. Those kept from public ordinances by sickness or other real hinderances, may expect the Saviour's gracious presence; he will soothe their sorrows, and abate their pains. Observe how numerous the patients were. When others speed well with Christ, it should quicken us in seeking after him. Christ departed into a solitary place. Though he was in no danger of distraction, or of temptation to vain-glory, yet he retired. Those who have the most business in public, and of the best kind, must yet sometimes be alone with God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
